What is an Event?

An event is something that happens in the browser.

Examples:

Clicking a button
Typing in a textbox
Moving the mouse
Pressing a keyboard key
Submitting a form

JavaScript listens for these events and executes code.

1. Click Event ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
HTML
<button onclick="showMessage()">Click Me</button>
JavaScript
function showMessage() {
    alert("Button Clicked!");
}

When you click the button, an alert appears.

Another Example
HTML
<h1 id="title">JavaScript</h1>

<button onclick="changeText()">
    Change Text
</button>
JavaScript
function changeText() {
    document.getElementById("title").textContent =
        "Welcome Priya!";
}
2. addEventListener() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

This is the recommended way to handle events.

HTML
<button id="btn">Click Me</button>
JavaScript
let button = document.getElementById("btn");

button.addEventListener("click", function () {
    alert("Button Clicked");
});
Using Arrow Functions
button.addEventListener("click", () => {
    console.log("Hello");
});
Why Use addEventListener()?

❌ Avoid this:

<button onclick="showMessage()">

✅ Prefer this:

button.addEventListener("click", showMessage);

Benefits:

Keeps HTML clean.
Allows multiple event listeners.
Easier to maintain.
3. Input Event ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Runs whenever the user types.

HTML
<input type="text" id="username">
JavaScript
let input = document.getElementById("username");

input.addEventListener("input", function () {
    console.log(input.value);
});

Typing:

P
Pr
Pri
Priya

Console:

P
Pr
Pri
Priya
Display Input on Screen
HTML
<input id="name">

<h2 id="output"></h2>
JavaScript
let nameInput = document.getElementById("name");
let output = document.getElementById("output");

nameInput.addEventListener("input", () => {
    output.textContent = nameInput.value;
});
4. Submit Event ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
HTML
<form id="loginForm">

<input type="text" id="username">

<button type="submit">
Login
</button>

</form>
JavaScript
let form = document.getElementById("loginForm");

form.addEventListener("submit", function (event) {

    event.preventDefault();

    alert("Form Submitted");

});
What is preventDefault()?

Normally, a form reloads the page after submission.

preventDefault() stops that behavior.

5. Keyboard Events ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Common keyboard events:

keydown
keyup
keydown
document.addEventListener("keydown", function (event) {

    console.log(event.key);

});

Press:

A

Console:

a
Detect Enter Key
document.addEventListener("keydown", function (event) {

    if (event.key === "Enter") {

        console.log("Enter Pressed");

    }

});
6. Mouse Events ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Common mouse events:

click
dblclick
mouseover
mouseout
mousedown
mouseup
Mouse Over
HTML
<h1 id="title">
Move Mouse Here
</h1>
JavaScript
let title = document.getElementById("title");

title.addEventListener("mouseover", function () {

    title.style.color = "red";

});
Mouse Out
title.addEventListener("mouseout", function () {

    title.style.color = "black";

});
Double Click
button.addEventListener("dblclick", () => {

    alert("Double Clicked");

});
Event Object ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Every event handler receives an event object.

button.addEventListener("click", function (event) {

    console.log(event);

});

Useful properties:

event.target
event.type
event.key
Example
button.addEventListener("click", function (event) {

    console.log(event.target);

});

Output

<button>Click Me</button>
Multiple Event Listeners
button.addEventListener("click", function () {

    console.log("First");

});

button.addEventListener("click", function () {

    console.log("Second");

});

Output

First
Second

Common Mistakes
❌ Calling the Function Immediately

Wrong

button.addEventListener("click", showMessage());

The function runs immediately.

✅ Correct
button.addEventListener("click", showMessage);

or

button.addEventListener("click", () => {

    showMessage();

});
❌ Forgetting preventDefault()

If you don't call:

event.preventDefault();

the form reloads the page.
